featured_reviews.review_id: Damdi Masjid, a historical place in Ahmednagar, built in 1568 during the Ahmednagar Sultanate. Its elegant architecture with pointed arches, slender minarets, and a trefoil-patterned parapet wall reflects the craftsmanship of its time. Legend has it that the mosque was constructed with contributions from the local Fakirs and laborers, adding a unique community touch. The interior is divided into six bays, showcasing thoughtful design. A must-visit monument of national importance. However, there's a need for better infrastructure in the surrounding area, which would further enhance the experience for visitors and help preserve this cultural treasure.

featured_reviews.review_id:
A historical monument, a mosque with a beautiful and perfect stone carving out of black stone. If you are a history lover and love to visit places with a story, you can certainly visit this place. Early morning is the best time to visit since sunlight falls from opposite direction and it's good time for photography.

Notice the flat ceiling from inside that has two-way arrow signs on it. I am still trying to find out something more about this specific phenomenon. Will keep posted on any update.

featured_reviews.review_id: This is a large mosque built at an elevation of about fifteen feet from the ground and quite large. Our guide told us that it took twenty five years to build it. There is a lot of minute work on the minarets as well as inside the mosque. It has a mix of Hindu and Islamic architecture as there are a large of pillars inside the main hall of the mosque. On the roof, on can see very intricate art work similar that seen in Jain temples. There is a unique prayer hall for women in that mosque. There is a well-maintained garden and it is a UNESCO heritage structure. Well-worth visiting!

A little further from Bhingar on Ahmednagar Pathardi road, this place currently has a mosque and a baradari. A tomb has been built today at the place where Emperor Aurangzeb took bath. caaNd biibii (1550-1599), jinheN caaNd khaatuun yaa caaNd sultaanaa ke naam se bhii jaanaa jaataa hai, ek bhaartiiy muslim mhilaa yoddhaa thii /  unhoNne biijaapur (1596-1599) aur ahmdngr (1580-1590) kii sNrkssk ke ruup meN kaam kiyaa thaa / [1] caaNd biibii ko sbse jyaadaa smraatt akbr kii mugl senaa se ahmdngr kii rkssaa ke lie jaanaa jaataa hai /  jo aaj bhii jntaa ke lie itihaas ke taur pr adbhut priicy detaa hai

ek gtthbNdhn niiti kaa anusrnn krte hue caaNd biibii kii shaadii biijaapur sltnt ke alii aadil shaah prthm se huii thii / [4] unke pti dvaaraa biijaapur kii puurvii siimaa ke paas ek kueN (baavdd'ii) kaa nirmaann kraayaa gyaa aur unke naam pr baavdd'ii kaa naam caaNd baavdd'ii rkhaa gyaa thaa / [5]
alii aadil shaah ke pitaa, ibraahim aadil shaah prthm ne sunnii riisoN, hbshiyoN aur ddekkn ke biic shkti kaa vibhaajn kr diyaa thaa /  tthaapi, alii aadil shaah ne shiyaa kaa pkss liyaa thaa / [6] 1580 meN unkii mRtyu ke baad, shiyaa riisoN ne apne nau vrssiiy bhtiije ibraahim aadil shaah dvitiiy ko shaask ghossit kr diyaa /  [7] ddekkn senaanaayk kmaal kh'aan ne raajy pr kbj'aa kr liyaa aur sNrkssk bn ge /  kmaal kh'aan ne caaNd biibii kaa anaadr kiyaa jinko aisaa lgtaa thaa ki kmaal kh'aan kii siNhaasn hdd'pne kii mhtvaakaaNkssaa hai /  caaNd biibii ne any senaanaayk haajii kishvr kh'aan kii mdd se kmaal kh'aan ke khilaaph hmle kii saajish rcii.[7] kmaal kh'aan us smy pkdd'e ge jb vo bhaag rhe the aur unheN kile meN maut kii sjaa dii gyii / 
kishvr kh'aan ibrhim ke duusre sNrkssk bn ge /  dhraaseo meN ahmdngr sltnt ke khilaaph ek ldd'aaii meN unke netRtv meN biijaapur kii senaa ne dushmn senaa ke sb topkhaanoN aur haathiyoN pr kbjaa kr liyaa /  jiit ke baad kishvr kh'aan ne any biijaapurii senaanaaykoN ko aadesh diyaa ki ve kbjaae ge sbhii haathiyoN ko chodd' deN /  haathii behd mhtvpuurnn the aur any senaanaaykoN ne ise bhyNkr apraadh ke ruup meN liyaa /  caaNd biibii ke saath, unhoNne baaNkaapur ke senaanaayk mustphaa kh'aan kii mdd se kishvr kh'aan ko khtm krne kii yojnaa rcii. kishvr kh'aan ke jaasuusoN ne unheN saajish ke baare meN btaayaa /  kishvr kh'aan ne mustphaa kh'aan ke khilaaph apne sainikoN ko bhejaa jo ldd'aaii meN pkdd'e ge aur maar die ge / [7] caaNd biibii ne kishvr kh'aan ko cunautii dii lekin usne unheN staaraa kile meN kaid kr liyaa aur apne aap ko raajaa ghossit krne kii koshish kii /  lekin, kishvr kh'aan baakii senaanaaykoN ke biic bhut alokpriy ho gyaa thaa /  vh us smy bhaagne ke lie mjbuur ho gyaa jb hbshii senaanaayk ikhlaas kh'aan ke netRtv meN ek sNyukt senaa ne biijaapur pr hmlaa kr diyaa /  senaa meN tiin hbshii riisoN, ikhlaas kh'aan, haamid kh'aan aur dilaavr kh'aan kii senaa shaamil thii / [6] kishvr kh'aan ne ahmdngr meN apnii kismt aajmaane kii asphl koshish kii aur phir golkuNddaa ke lie bhaag ge /  vh nirvaasn meN mustphaa kh'aan ke ek rishtedaar dvaaraa maar die ge /  is ke baad, caaNd biibii ne thodd'e smy ke lie ek sNrkssk ke ruup meN kaam kiyaa / [7]
iske baad ikhlaas kh'aan sNrkssk bn ge lekin vh shiighr hii caaNd biibii dvaaraa brkhaast kr die ge /  baad meN unhoNne phir se apnii taanaashaahii shuruu kr dii jise jld hii any hbshii senaanaaykoN dvaaraa cunautii dii gyii / [6] biijaapur meN sthiti kaa laabh utthaate hue ahmdngr ke nijaam shaahii sultaan ne golkuNddaa ke kutub shaahii ke saath milkr biijaapur pr hmlaa bol diyaa /  biijaapur meN uplbdh sainik sNyukt hmleN kaa saamnaa krne ke lie pryaapt nhiiN the / [7] hbshii senaanaaykoN ko ehsaas huaa ki ve akele shhr kii rkssaa nhiiN kr skteN aur unhoNne caaNd biibii ko apnaa istiiphaa de diyaa /  [6] caaNd biibii dvaaraa niyukt ek shiyaa senaanaayk abuu-ul-hsn, ne krnaattk meN mraatthaa senaa ko bulaayaa /  mraatthoN ne aakrmnnkaariyoN kii aapuurti laainoN[7] pr hmlaa kr diyaa aur mjbuur hokr ahmdngr-golkuNddaa kii sNyukt senaa vaaps lautt gyii / 
phir ikhlaas kh'aan ne biijaapur pr adhikaar paane ke lie dilaavr kh'aan pr hmlaa kr diyaa /  haalaaNki, vh haar ge the aur 1582 se 1591 tk ke lie dilaavr kh'aan sNrkssk bn ge / [6] jb biijaapur raajy meN shaaNti bhaal huii to caaNd biibii ahmdngr meN lautt aaii.

iske baad ikhlaas kh'aan sNrkssk bn ge lekin vh shiighr hii caaNd biibii dvaaraa brkhaast kr die ge /  baad meN unhoNne phir se apnii taanaashaahii shuruu kr dii jise jld hii any hbshii senaanaaykoN dvaaraa cunautii dii gyii / [6] biijaapur meN sthiti kaa laabh utthaate hue ahmdngr ke nijaam shaahii sultaan ne golkuNddaa ke kutub shaahii ke saath milkr biijaapur pr hmlaa bol diyaa /  biijaapur meN uplbdh sainik sNyukt hmleN kaa saamnaa krne ke lie pryaapt nhiiN the / [7] hbshii senaanaaykoN ko ehsaas huaa ki ve akele shhr kii rkssaa nhiiN kr skteN aur unhoNne caaNd biibii ko apnaa istiiphaa de diyaa /  [6] caaNd biibii dvaaraa niyukt ek shiyaa senaanaayk abuu-ul-hsn, ne krnaattk meN mraatthaa senaa ko bulaayaa /  mraatthoN ne aakrmnnkaariyoN kii aapuurti laainoN[7] pr hmlaa kr diyaa aur mjbuur hokr ahmdngr-golkuNddaa kii sNyukt senaa vaaps lautt gyii / 
phir ikhlaas kh'aan ne biijaapur pr adhikaar paane ke lie dilaavr kh'aan pr hmlaa kr diyaa /  haalaaNki, vh haar ge the aur 1582 se 1591 tk ke lie dilaavr kh'aan sNrkssk bn ge / [6] jb biijaapur raajy meN shaaNti bhaal huii to caaNd biibii ahmdngr meN lautt aaii.

Chand Bibi (1550-1599), also known as Chand Khatun or Chand Sultana, was an Indian Muslim female warrior. She served as the regent of Bijapur (1596-1599) and Ahmednagar (1580-1590).[1] Chand Bibi is best known for defending Ahmednagar from Emperor Akbar's Mughal forces. Which even today gives a wonderful introduction to the public as history.

Following an alliance policy, Chand Bibi was married to Ali Adil Shah I of the Bijapur Sultanate.[4] A well (stepwell) near the eastern border of Bijapur was built by her husband and the stepwell is named after her. Chand Bawdi was kept.[5]
Ali Adil Shah's father, Ibrahim Adil Shah I, had divided power between the Sunni nobles, the Habshis and the Deccan. However, Ali Adil Shah took the Shia side.[6] After his death in 1580, the Shia nobles proclaimed his nine-year-old nephew Ibrahim Adil Shah II as ruler. [7] The Deccan general Kamal Khan captured the kingdom and became the protectorate. Kamal Khan disrespected Chand Bibi who felt that Kamal Khan had ambitions to usurp the throne. Chand Bibi planned an attack against Kamal Khan with the help of another general, Haji Kishwar Khan.[7] Kamal Khan was caught while he was on the run and was sentenced to death in the fort.
Kishwar Khan became Ibrahim's second guardian. In a battle against the Ahmednagar Sultanate at Dharaseo, the Bijapur army under his leadership captured all the artillery and elephants of the enemy army. After the victory, Kishwar Khan ordered the other Bijapuri generals to release all the captured elephants. The elephants were extremely important and the other generals took this as a heinous crime. Along with Chand Bibi, he hatched a plan to eliminate Kishwar Khan with the help of Mustafa Khan, the general of Bankapur. Kishwar Khan's spies told him about the plot. Kishwar Khan sent his troops against Mustafa Khan who were captured and killed in the battle.[7] Chand Bibi challenged Kishwar Khan but he imprisoned her in the Satara fort and tried to declare himself king. Did. But, Kishwar Khan had become very unpopular among the rest of the generals. He was forced to flee when a combined army led by Habshi general Ikhlas Khan attacked Bijapur. The army consisted of three Habshi nobles, Ikhlas Khan, Hamid Khan and Dilawar Khan.[6] Kishwar Khan unsuccessfully tried his luck at Ahmednagar and then fled to Golconda. He was killed in exile by a relative of Mustafa Khan. After this, Chand Bibi acted as a mentor for a short period of time.[7]
After this Ikhlas Khan became the guardian but he was soon dismissed by Chand Bibi. Later he resumed his autocracy which was soon challenged by other Habshi generals.[6] Taking advantage of the situation in Bijapur, the Nizam Shahi Sultan of Ahmednagar along with the Qutb Shahi of Golconda attacked Bijapur. The troops available in Bijapur were not sufficient to withstand the combined attack. [7] The Habshi generals realized that they could not defend the city alone and tendered their resignation to Chand Bibi. [6] Abu-ul-Hasan, a Shia general appointed by Chand Bibi, summoned the Maratha army to Karnataka. The Marathas attacked the invaders' supply lines[7] and the Ahmednagar-Golkonda combined forces were forced to withdraw.
Then Ikhlas Khan attacked Dilawar Khan to get control over Bijapur. However, he was defeated and Dilawar Khan became the regent from 1582 to 1591. [6] When peace was restored to the Bijapur kingdom, Chand Bibi returned to Ahmednagar.
